e approach, as opposed to a collection of regional histories, deftly weaving together different themes. With debates around globalization, migration, global finance and environmental change intensifying, this authoritative account of the relationship between colonialism and economic development makes an invaluable contribution to several distinct literatures in economic history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Economic History.2bisacsh1 aRoy, Tirthankar, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBristol UP/Policy Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311119671840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781529207651423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781529207651/original  a978-3-11-119671-8  Bristol UP/Policy Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles